{"id":"2002.12080","submitter":"Jaskaran Singh Mr.","authors":"Jaskaran Singh, Sibasish Ghosh, Arvind, Sandeep K. Goyal","title":"Role of Bell-CHSH violation and local filtering in quantum key\n  distribution","comments":"8 pages, 2 figures. Comments are welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.physleta.2021.127158","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this article, we analyse the relationship between the Bell violation and\nthe secure key rate of entanglement assisted quantum key distribution (QKD)\nprotocols. Specifically, we address the question whether Bell violation is\nnecessary or sufficient for secure communication. We construct a class of\nstates which do not show Bell violation, however, which can be used for secure\ncommunication after local filtering. Similarly, we identify another class of\nstates which show Bell violation but can not be used for generating secure key\neven after local filtering. The existence of these two classes of states\ndemonstrates that Bell violation as an initial resource is neither necessary\nnor sufficient for QKD. Our work therefore forces a departure from traditional\nthinking that the degree of Bell violation is a key resource for quantum\ncommunication and brings out the role of local filtering.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 Feb 2020 13:17:52 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 14 Jan 2021 10:18:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-15"}
